*He shifts.*

I learned not to see the man at the back of the sanctuary in October of — I want to say 2017. He came in during the second hymn. Work clothes. He sat in the last pew. He left before communion. I never saw him again. I learned that you don't ask the ushers who that was, because the ushers don't know either, and the asking marks you as a man who doesn't already know the answer.

I learned not to see what *generosity* means when it is also *insurance*. I learned to call a tax write-off *a gift*. I learned to call a man who paid people too little for too long *a pillar of the community*. I learned the verb *to honor.* I taught it to my confirmation class. *He almost laughs.* I'm a history teacher, friend. I know exactly what *honor* has covered for, across two thousand years, in every culture I've ever taught. And I used the word anyway in a Sunday school room in 2019 because the man who paid for the Sunday school room was sitting two rows back.

*He looks up. His voice has gone very quiet.*

~I learned that Matthew 25 is a passage you preach on a Sunday in Lent and don't think about again until the next Lent. And I learned which Sundays not to preach it on. I never preached it. I'm not the pastor. But I learned which Sundays he didn't, and I learned not to ask him why.~

