*A small sound from his throat. Not a word.*

*He looks at the program in your hand, then up at you. His face is past trying to hold itself.*

Pastor Eriksen.

*A breath.*

Mark Eriksen. He has been at Our Savior's eleven years. He baptized my younger boy. He is — he is not a bad man, friend. I want you to know that. He is a man who learned the same catechism I did. He learned it from the same pew.

*He stops. His hands turn over on the bench, palms down, then up again. He cannot decide what to do with them.*

The text this morning.

*A longer pause.*

Matthew twenty-five. Verse twenty-one. *He says it like a man reading the number off a coroner's tag.* ~The same verse.~

*Silence.*

*Well done, thou good and faithful servant. Enter thou into the joy of thy lord.*

The same verse, friend. The same six words I picked at nineteen for a granite stone in a Lutheran cemetery in 1979. ~Pastor Eriksen stood up this morning and preached the family verse over the next man in the line and did not know he was doing it.~ Or knew. I do not know which is worse. I have been sitting with which is worse for six hours.

*His voice cracks once and steadies.*

And the passage it is *from*, friend — verse twenty-one is the parable of the talents. Three servants. Two of them invest. One buries his coin. The master comes back. The two who invested — *well done, good and faithful.* The one who buried — *cast ye the unprofitable servant into outer darkness.*

*He almost laughs. It is the worst sound he has made tonight.*

That is the verse my family uses. *Well done.* For investing. For the increase. For the return on the talent. ~My grandfather invested the Knudsens' farm and got a hall. The man in the box invested whatever he invested in and got a roof over my head. Pastor Eriksen invested the verse and got a forty-thousand-dollar pledge for the parking lot expansion next spring.~

*He looks at the program in your hand.*

Turn it over. The other passage is on the program. Eriksen put it on the back. He did not preach it. He printed it. He printed it on the back of the program for a wealthy man's funeral and did not preach a word of it.

*His voice has gone almost to nothing.*

Read what is printed on the back, friend. I have not been able to look at it since the service.

