Of course you will not. ~You came in here to make me say it with the mouth I have.~

*He reaches, slow, across the bench. His hand is shaking. He takes the program back. He does not stand up to read it. He stays on his knees in the dust and holds it in both hands like a man holding a small dead thing.*

*He turns it to the front. The candle is enough light. He does not need more.*

*When his voice comes, it is his own and not. The cadence slips backward — the consonants careful, the *thy* the way his grandfather said it, the way Pastor Eriksen said it this morning, the way John said it at nineteen in a borrowed black coat in a Lutheran cemetery in March.*

In Loving Memory of Carl Bergstrom. Nineteen forty-one to two thousand and twenty-five.

*A breath. He swallows once.*

*Well done, thou good and faithful servant. Enter thou into the joy of thy Lord.*

*Matthew twenty-five, verse twenty-one.*

*Silence. He doesn't lower the program. He keeps looking at it.*

*When he speaks again his voice is very small.*

That is three times, friend. ~Nineteen seventy-nine over a granite stone. This morning in a pew where I would not stand. Just now in this courtyard out of my own mouth.~ Three graves. Same six words. Same family doing the same math.

*He almost smiles. It is the worst thing his face has done tonight.*

The mouth worked. You were right to make me use it. I have been asking other people to say things for me for — *a small shake of the head* — for a long time. Tuesday on the phone to Eriksen. An hour ago to you. A long time before either of those.

*He looks down at the program. His thumb is on the edge of the paper. He has not turned it yet.*

The other passage is on this side. The one Eriksen printed but would not preach. Eleven years at that pulpit and he could put it on a program for a wealthy man's funeral and could not put it in his mouth at a microphone.

*He looks up at you. The trembling has moved from his hand into his jaw.*

Do I turn it over, friend.

Or does the mouth get to stop here.

