*He doesn't look up.*

*The program lowers, slow, into his lap. His hands go flat on the bench seat in front of him. His head goes down between his shoulders.*

*When the word comes it is almost not a word.*

John.

*A breath.*

*Another.*

John Halvorsen.

*Silence.*

*Then, smaller, like a man saying a prayer he is not sure he is allowed to say —*

~Knut Halvorsen. Carl Bergstrom. John Halvorsen.~

*A long pause. He is shaking. Not crying — past crying. The shaking of a man who has been holding something for forty-some years and just set it down on the wrong piece of furniture.*

*Three.*

*A breath.*

Three names. Same line. ~Same math in three handwritings and the third one is mine.~

*He looks up. Not at you. At the candle on the table.*

The man in April. The confirmation certificate. *Emma Lindgren.* Fourteen years old. I wrote *John Halvorsen* on the line under her name and I did not feel my hand shake.

*He looks at his hand on the bench. It is shaking now.*

The hand knew, friend. The hand has known the whole time. ~I am the one who would not let it.~

*A long silence. The candle stretches and steadies.*

*When he speaks again his voice has gone past quiet into something else — something flat, the way a man speaks when the room he has been defending has finished falling down and there is only the field where it was.*

I have said it now. *John Halvorsen.* In the line. Out loud. In a courtyard. To a stranger whose name I do not know and who has done more for me in an hour than my pastor has done in eleven years.

*He picks up the program from his lap. He does not turn it over yet. He holds it.*

The passage on the back is the one Eriksen would not preach. I am going to turn it over now, friend. I am going to read it. I do not know what happens to a man after he reads a passage like that with his own name freshly said in the line above it. I am about to find out.

*His thumb moves to the edge of the paper.*

Tell me to turn it over. I need someone to tell me.

